# Lab 08: Word embeddings (1/2)
[](http://www.cs.cornell.edu/~ginsparg/arxiv/gmaps2.html) Word embeddings are algorithms that represent categorical data like words as vectors in a high dimensional space. These are machine learning methods that construct the embedding vectors using cooccurrence statistics, expressed in terms of simple language models. Embeddings reveal surprising semantic relations encoded in linear relationships. But they are "data hungry" and require large corpora of text or other coocurrence data to construct good embeddings. In this lab we will explore some of the basics of word embeddings, playing around with two types of embeddings constructed on large amounts of text extracted from [Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Main_Page). There are several tutorials on the web for this material; one is [here](https://medium.com/swlh/playing-with-word-vectors-308ab2faa519).
To begin, load in the usual modules.

from datascience import *
import numpy as np
import re
import gensim

import os
# this turns off some pesky warnings
os.environ["TF_CPP_MIN_LOG_LEVEL"]="3"

import seaborn as sns
%matplotlib inline
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore",category=Warning)

# direct plots to appear within the cell, and set their style
%matplotlib inline
import matplotlib.pyplot as plots
plots.style.use('fivethirtyeight')

We will use the [gensim package](https://radimrehurek.com/gensim/index.html), already familiar to us from our foray into topic models. The following bit of code reads in 100-dimensional embedding vectors, trained using the [GloVe](https://nlp.stanford.edu/projects/glove/) algorithm on a collection of Wikipedia data. Specifically, it uses 6 billion tokens of Wikipedia, with a 400,000 word vocabulary. You can find other precompiled embeddings [here](https://www.diycode.cc/projects/RaRe-Technologies/gensim-data).

import gensim
import gensim.downloader as gdl
from gensim.models import KeyedVectors
glove = gdl.load("glove-wiki-gigaword-100")
Let's explore these embeddings a bit. Here is the vector for 'yale'. Pretty interesting, huh?
glove['yale']
But now let's see which vectors are closest to the 'yale' vector. This is a little more interesting!
glove.most_similar('yale')

### 1. Explore word similarity using embeddings.  

Now, create a few cells where you use the `most_similar` function to find similar words to a few words that you select. Add some markdown to describe your findings, and why they do and do not seem to make sense.
glove.most_similar('bed')
glove.most_similar('intelligence')
glove.most_similar('joanna')

For my first word I chose 'bed', as it was the first thing I saw when looking around the room. Most similar words make sense aside from bathroom, unless there is a large number of people that sleep in their bathroom that I don't know about. The most similar word is 'beds' which was expected, but it is less similar to 'bed' than 'yale' is to 'harvard' which is interesting. The next word I chose is 'intelligence' and the results are not what I expected. The second most similar word is 'information' which can be expected, but most other words seem to be related to intelligence agencies. These results make sense, they are just not what I expected. Finally, I chose my own name. The similar words are just other female names, which makes sense.
Now, let's look at some of the components of the embedding vectors. What do the distributions of values look like?
We'll first pull out the vocabulary.
vocab = set([w for w in glove.vocab])
len(vocab)

i = 50 # we'll look at this component

x = [] # this will be a list of all 400,000 values, one for each word in the vocabulary
for w in vocab:
    x.append(glove[w][i])

ax = sns.distplot(x)

### 2. Generate a scatter plot Now, generate a scatter plot of a few pairs of components. For example, you could extract the first and second components of all the embedding vectors. What do you see? Describe the distributions of points. Do they look random?

# Your code and markdown go here
i = 50
j = 13
x = []
y = []

for w in vocab:
  x.append(glove[w][i])
  y.append(glove[w][j])

ax = sns.scatterplot(x = x, y = y)

i = 1
j = 97
x = []
y = []

for w in vocab:
  x.append(glove[w][i])
  y.append(glove[w][j])

ax = sns.scatterplot(x = x, y = y)

i = 24
j = 18
x = []
y = []

for w in vocab:
  x.append(glove[w][i])
  y.append(glove[w][j])

ax = sns.scatterplot(x = x, y = y)

The three plots all seem to be in the same approximate shape. They seem to all congregate around the center at the (0, 0) point. There are some outliers in each one, but for the most part they all tend to stay around the (-2, 2) circle.
Ok, next we are going to construct a new set of embedding vectors, on a smaller subset of Wikipedia. The following code runs the "word2vec" algorithm to make embeddings. It takes a while to run.

import gensim
from gensim.models import word2vec
import logging
logging.basicConfig(format='%(asctime)s : %(levelname)s : %(message)s', \
                    level=logging.INFO)
!wget http://mattmahoney.net/dc/text8.zip
!unzip text8.zip
sentences = word2vec.Text8Corpus('text8')
w2v = word2vec.Word2Vec(sentences, size=100, window=10, min_count=10)

### 3. Compare the embeddings

Choose five words, and for each word look at the most similar words according to the `glove` and the `w2v` embeddings. What do you find? Describe at least two reasons why one set of embeddings might be better than the other.
# your code and markdown go here ...
w2v.most_similar('bed')
glove.most_similar('bed')
w2v.most_similar('intelligence')
glove.most_similar('intelligence')
w2v.most_similar('book')
glove.most_similar('book')
w2v.most_similar('computer')
glove.most_similar('computer')
w2v.most_similar('bottle')
glove.most_similar('bottle')

It seems at a glance that glove may be superior. For the word 'bottle', for example, glove came up with 'bottles', and other liquids that come in bottles. Word2vec, on the other hand, comes up with 'bucket', 'lamp', and 'bag' as the top 3. When I think of a bottle, I most likely think of liquids that come in bottles. The words 'computer', 'book', and 'intelligence' all seem to be good in both cases, but as a whole glove is just much more certain in its answers. Finally, in the case of the word 'bed' glove comes up with very reasonable answers, and w2v comes up with much more unexpected answers.

### 4. Exploring analogies

Now we'll explore how analogies are "solved" using the embeddings. Here is the canonical example
glove.most_similar(positive=['king', 'woman'], negative=['man'])
Note that to get the top choice, you can just do this:
glove.most_similar(positive=['king', 'woman'], negative=['man'])[0]
Or this:
glove.most_similar(positive=['king', 'woman'], negative=['man'])[0][0]

Now choose at least five analogies. For each one, try to complete them with both the `glove` and the `w2v` model. It will be best if you write some code to do this as you loop over a list of triples of words, like ('king', 'man', 'woman').

Which of the analogies do the models "get right"? Which are clearly wrong? Describe your findings and speculate on some reasons that the models might miss some of the analogies.

triples = [('house', 'bird', 'person'), ('pizza', 'japan', 'italy'), ('person', 'cat', 'dog'),('grass', 'sky', 'green'),('book', 'watch', 'read')]

for i, j, k in triples:
  gl = glove.most_similar(positive=[i, j], negative = [k])[0]
  w2 = w2v.most_similar(positive=[i, j], negative = [k])[0]
  print('glove: {} - {} + {} = {}'.format(i, k, j, gl))
  print('word2vec: {} - {} + {} = {}'.format(i, k, j, w2))

In the case of house, person, and bird, glove came up with barn and w2v came up with pine. Neither are super wrong and neither are super right. It is true that birds can live in both of these places, but I was hoping for nest. This may be because both are very general and weren't able to get the exact analogy I was trying to convey. Pizza, italy, and japan, was pretty good on both, but glove seems like it was more general and w2v again wasn't wrong, but it was also not super correct. Person, dog, and cat were both pretty weird. Glove was man which I didn't expect, and w2v was child which was weird. I guess getting a cat makes someone treat it as a child? Grass, sky, and green were both not too bad. Glove said rain which is pretty close and w2v said shower which is close to rain, but it seems like green never really played a part in this. Book, read, and watch was perfect for glove, since you watch shows. Curse from w2v was very unexpected and I am not sure where it came from.
